 dist = 1\nOutput: 0\nExplanation:\nThere are no people who are not \"it\" to catch.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: team = [0], dist = 1\nOutput: 0\nExplanation:\nThere are no people who are \"it\" to catch people.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= team.length <= 105\n0 <= team[i] <= 1\n1 <= dist <= team.length\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def catchMaximumAmountofPeople(self, team: List[int], dist: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def catchMaximumAmountofPeople(self, team: List[int], dist: int) -> int:\n        n = len(team)\n        caught = 0\n        i, j = 0, 0\n        \n        while i < n and j < n:\n            if team[i] == 0:  # Look for someone who is not \"it\"\n                i += 1\n            elif team[j] == 1:  # Look for someone who is \"it\"\n                j += 1\n            else:\n                if i < j - dist or i > j + dist:\n                    # If the current \"it\" cannot catch the current \"not it\", move the pointers\n                    if i < j - dist:\n                        i += 1\n                    else:\n                        j += 1\n                else:\n                    # If the current \"it\" can catch the current \"not it\", count the catch\n                    caught += 1\n                    i += 1\n                    j += 1\n        \n        return caught\n```\n\nThis solution uses two pointers to iterate through the `team` array. One pointer (`i`) looks for people who are not \"it\" (0s), and the other pointer (`j`) looks for people who are \"it\" (1s). The algorithm checks if the current \"it\" can catch the current \"not it\" within the given distance `dist`. If they can, it counts a catch and moves both pointers forward. If not, it moves the pointer of the person who is out of range forward. This ensures that we maximize the number of catches while respecting the constraints.", "estimated_date": 1630195200000}